# SQL Queries - Employee Satisfaction Analysis

This document contains all SQL queries used to analyze employee satisfaction data and identify key insights for the dashboard.

## Database Schema
- **Table:** employeesurvey.employees
- **Records:** 3,025 employees
- **Key Fields:** JobSatisfaction, Stress, WLB, Dept, JobLevel, haveOT, TrainingHoursPerYear, SleepHours, CommuteMode

---

## Query 1: Distribution of Satisfaction Scores

Shows how many employees fall into each satisfaction level (1-5).

```sql
SELECT 
  JobSatisfaction,
  COUNT(*) as employee_count,
  ROUND(COUNT(*) * 100.0 / (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM employeesurvey.employees), 2) as percentage
FROM employeesurvey.employees
GROUP BY JobSatisfaction
ORDER BY JobSatisfaction;
```

**Purpose:** Understand overall satisfaction distribution. Result: 58% satisfied (4-5) but 23% dissatisfied (1-2).

---

## Query 2: Satisfaction by Department

Aggregates key metrics (satisfaction, stress, WLB) by department to identify which departments need intervention.

```sql
SELECT 
  Dept,
  COUNT(*) as total_employees,
  ROUND(AVG(JobSatisfaction), 2) as avg_satisfaction,
  ROUND(AVG(Stress), 2) as avg_stress,
  ROUND(AVG(WLB), 2) as avg_wlb
FROM employeesurvey.employees
GROUP BY Dept
ORDER BY avg_satisfaction DESC;
```

**Purpose:** Identify department performance gaps. Result: Sales leads (3.50), IT lags (3.28). 0.22-point variance shows manageable departmental differences.

---

## Query 3: Key Drivers of Employee Satisfaction

Uses conditional aggregation (CASE WHEN) to test which factors have the strongest impact on satisfaction.

```sql
SELECT 
  'Stress' as factor,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN Stress <= 2 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as low_factor_satisfaction,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN Stress >= 4 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as high_factor_satisfaction
FROM employeesurvey.employees
UNION ALL
SELECT 
  'Work-Life Balance' as factor,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN WLB <= 2 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as low_factor_satisfaction,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN WLB >= 4 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as high_factor_satisfaction
FROM employeesurvey.employees
UNION ALL
SELECT 
  'Workload' as factor,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN Workload <= 2 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as low_factor_satisfaction,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN Workload >= 4 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as high_factor_satisfaction
FROM employeesurvey.employees
UNION ALL
SELECT 
  'Sleep Hours' as factor,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN SleepHours < 6 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as low_factor_satisfaction,
  ROUND(AVG(CASE WHEN SleepHours >= 8 THEN JobSatisfaction END), 2) as high_factor_satisfaction
FROM employeesurvey.employees;
```

**Purpose:** Identify which factors drive satisfaction most. Result: Work-Life Balance has 2.5-point differential (largest), making it the #1 intervention lever.

